 together the English past, present, and near future in a complete and continuous story. Yet all four authors also register their concern that historical loss may be an inevitable feature of a "modern" England, and they come to see their narratives as long tapestries that spontaneously rip apart as they grow, obliging the weaver to return to repair them. Focusing on Renaissance England's perplexing sense of its time-boundedness, Escobedo presents early national consciousness as stranded awkwardly between the premodern and modern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aLiterature and historyxHistoryxEngland. 0aNationalism and literaturexHistoryy16th centuryxEngland. 0aNationalism and literaturexHistoryy17th centuryxEngland. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501723964423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501723964.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG